ume demonstrates that the vast and growing commercial interactions between the countries of eastern Asia have long historical roots. The so-called “opening” to Western trade in the mid-nineteenth century, which is typically seen as the beginning of this process, is shown to be rather the reversal of a relatively temporary phase of state consolidation in the long eighteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMerchant marinezEast AsiaxHistory. 0aMerchant marine--East Asia--History. 0aNavigationzEast AsiaxHistory. 0aNavigation--East Asia--History. 0aShippingzEast AsiaxHistory. 0aShipping--East Asia--History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aChin, James K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFujita, Kayoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasuda, Takashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIioka, Naoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKayoko, Fujita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiu, Shiuh-feng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMomoki, Shiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMomoki, Shirō, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Anthony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobinson, Kenneth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShiro, Momoki, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSun, Laichen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWade, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYamauchi, Shinji, 